description.plain:
On “Make Me a Song,” American singer-songwriter Eleanor Friedberger examines music through a spiritual lens. She was inspired to write the song after meeting a devout Christian songwriter who told her how his faith motivated him to write music; she imagines what it would be like to get the same fulfillment from music itself. With its religious theme, Friedberger has described the song as a companion to “In Between Stars.”

The song was released promotionally ahead of Friedberger’s fourth studio album, Rebound, on which it was the fifth track. An accompanying music video shows Friedberger seeking enlightenment through fitness and new-age spiritualism.

annotations:
In tube top and shorts that Vice called “pull-me-down”
 She’s got kind of a native vibe before that was so cool
 She’s got kind of a native vibe before I even knew who was who
 And he’s ignoring me like it’s 2001

In 2001, VICE magazine featured a photo of Friedberger in their legendary street fashion segment DOs and DON'Ts (she was a DO, obviously). The caption calls her a “fucking treat,” makes reference to her shorts and “native vibe,” and commends her for proving that “girls are better than boys.”



Friedberger elaborates:

…the day that photo was taken I made a big mistake regarding the person who I’m singing about – so I’m kind of referencing that picture and everything that surrounds it.

description.plain:
“Everything” is the third song (and, coincidentally, the third release) from American alternative singer-songwriter Eleanor Friedberger’s fourth solo album, Rebound.

The song finds Friedberger examining the life of a woman who can’t decide what she wants in life. Friedberger elaborated in an interview with Stereogum: “I tried to make a pop song about a complicated subject: Everything […] People seem to really like the line: ‘I mean two houses please.‘” The song’s production draws inspiration from '80s synth-pop.

The song was released on April 20, 2018, becoming the third song and second single to be shared from the then-forthcoming album. The song was well received by critics, who praised the song’s “shimmering synths and an earworm of a guitar line” and crowned it a “great pop song.”

annotations: A man in Greece, a girlfriend in Italy

Greece is a recurring setting on Rebound: It’s where Friedberger recorded the record, and the album was even named after a nightclub in Athens that inspired her.

Friedberger told Consequence of Sound that this line was, in fact, inspired by a Greek friend of hers, who “wanted to have kids, but she (also) wanted to have this really radical life…”
